SIMPLE: immediate
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Immediate
<hw>Im*me"di*ate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>imm⟦eacute⟧diat</ets>. See <er>In-</er> not, and
<er>Mediate</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Not separated in respect to
place by anything intervening; proximate; close; <as>as,
<ex>immediate</ex> contact</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>You are the most <qex>immediate</qex> to our throne.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Not deferred by an interval of time; present;
instant.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Assemble we <xex>immediate</xex> council.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Death . . . not yet inflicted, as he feared,⟦br⟧
By some <qex>immediate</qex> stroke.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Acting with nothing interposed or between, or
without the intervention of another object as a cause, means, or agency;
acting, perceived, or produced, directly; <as>as, an <ex>immediate</ex>
cause</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>immediate</qex> knowledge of the past is therefore
impossible.</q> <rj><qau>Sir. W. Hamilton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Immediate amputation</b></col> <fld>(Surg.)</fld>, <cd>an
amputation performed within the first few hours after an injury, and
before the the effects of the shock have passed away.</cd></cs></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Proximate; close; direct; next.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Immediately</ent>⟦br⟧
